<P>ORIGINAL LETTERS Written to the Earl of <HI>ARLINGTON</HI> BY <HI>Sir</HI> RICHARD BULSTRODE, ENVOY at the COURT of <HI>Bru&s;&s;els</HI> from King CHARLES II, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> CONTAINING The mo&s;t remarkable Tran&s;actions, both in Court and Camp, during his MINISTRY, particularly the Famous Battel of <HI>Seneff</HI>, between the Prince of <HI>Orange</HI> and the Prince of <HI>Conde</HI>.</P>
<P>WITH A PREFACE, Giving an Account of the AUTHOR's LIFE and FAMILY.</P>
<Q>Sera venit, &s;ed certa venit&mdash;</Q>
<P><HI>LONDON:</HI> Printed for <HI>R. Sare</HI> at <HI>Gray's-Inn-Gate</HI> in <HI>Holborn</HI>, and &s;old by <HI>J. Morphew</HI> near <HI>Stationers</HI> Hall. 1712.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="dedication">
<PB REF="2">
<HEAD>To the RIGHT HONOURABLE, GEORGE EARL of <HI>CARDIGAN</HI>, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE>MY LORD,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>ENcourag'd by Your Lord&s;hip's Permi&s;&s;ion, I pre&s;ume to in|&s;cribe Your Name to the fol|lowing Sheets. The Author of them, Sir <HI>Richard Bul&s;trode</HI>, was de&s;cended from a very ancient Family, to an Heire&s;s of which one of Your Lord|&s;hip's Ance&s;tors was marry'd, and the <HI>Bul&s;trodes</HI> now living have Rea&s;on to
<PB REF="3">
acknowledge it, as they do, to be no &s;mall Honour to them, that the Earl of CARDIGAN quarters their Arms.</P>
<P>My Lord, it would be next to im|pertinent to tell the World what they &s;ufficiently know already; that Your Lord&s;hip derives Your De&s;cent from a Race truly Noble, as well for the Length of their Duration, as for the Honours our Kings, in Reward of their Services, at &s;everal times conferr'd on them. They have for many Ages been Great in Title, and Good a|bove Greatne&s;s. Their Inclinations and Endeavours were the general Good of Mankind: They delighted in obliging others, and were pleas'd to &s;ee them pleas'd with their Bounty: They have been renown'd for relie|ving Merit in Want, and for &s;uccou|ring Vertue in Di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
<P>The&s;e and many other Vertues &s;eem an Inheritance in Your Lord&s;hip, and deriv'd from Your Ance&s;tors with Your Blood. My Lord, I cannot be
<PB REF="4">
guilty of Flattery if I would, nor needs there any Trial of Skill to &s;hew how I can prai&s;e: Nature has done it to my Hands, and repre&s;ented fai|rer Ideas than I can de&s;cribe: She has endow'd You with all her Ble&s;&s;ings; with a Gracefulne&s;s of Per&s;on, Ex|cellence of Under&s;tanding, Largene&s;s of Heart, with Integrity, and Ju&s;tice of Principles, with Humanity, Affa|bility, and many other Qualities, far above my De&s;cription, and that would &s;ecure me from the Cen&s;ure of Flat|tery, even though I &s;hould launch into a Panegyrick.</P>
<P>Fortune too, my Lord, in your Regard, has been more wi&s;e than u|&s;ual: for &s;he frequently honours and enriches others to her own Di&s;grace; but &s;he participates in the Prai&s;e, and commends her own Wi&s;dom, in what &s;he has be&s;tow'd on Your Lord&s;hip: Wealth is of &s;ome Value in Your Hands; and &s;o good an U&s;e is made of Your great E&s;tate, that even Envy
<PB REF="5">
does not wi&s;h it le&s;s. Be pleas'd, my Lord, to give me leave to &s;peak to You in the Words of <HI>Horace</HI>, which are &s;o ju&s;tly applicable to Your Lord&s;hip.</P>
<Q><L>Non Tu Corpus eras &s;ine Pectore: Dii Tibi Formam,</L>
<L><HI>Dii Tibi Divitias dederunt</HI>, artemque fruendi.</L></Q>
<P>But I come to beg Protection, not to give Prai&s;e: And my greate&s;t Am|bition, which I be&s;eech Your Lord|&s;hip to pardon, is, to &s;ub&s;cribe my &s;elf, with the mo&s;t profound Sub|mi&s;&s;ion and Re&s;pect,</P>
<CLOSER><SALUTE>MY LORD,</SALUTE>
<SIGNED><HI>Your Lord&s;hip's mo&s;t humble, and mo&s;t obedient Servant</HI>, E. BYSSHE.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="preface">
<PB REF="6">
<HEAD>THE PREFACE.</HEAD>
<P>SINCE mo&s;t of the Nations of <HI>Europe</HI> have been engag'd in Wars, how dif|ficult it has been to come at the true Knowledge of publick Occurrences, is evident from the different Relations, that have been given us of them; one would al|mo&s;t think, that we had not only engag'd in Leagues and Confederacies again&s;t one ano|ther, but that all of us in general were en|ter'd into one Grand Alliance, and had una|nimou&s;ly declar'd War again&s;t the Truth of Hi&s;tory: So artfully di&s;ingenuous have we &s;hewn our &s;elves in extenuating, di&s;gui&s;ing, and concealing our own Lo&s;&s;es, and in mag|nifying, mi&s;repre&s;enting, and publi&s;hing tho&s;e of the adver&s;e Party. Had the Common Ene|my been &s;even Years ago brought to that low Condition, to which it was then indu&s;triou&s;ly given out that he was, when it was even
<PB REF="7">
made a Mark of Di&s;affection to &s;ugge&s;t or believe the contrary, we &s;hould not at this Day be thus divided in Opinion concerning a &s;afe and honourable Peace, nor perplex'd with the Uncertainty, whether it were best to en|ter into a Treaty upon the Preliminaries now offer'd us.</P>
<P>But this Mi&s;repre&s;entation of the true Po|&s;ture of Affairs may be &s;o far indulg'd and excus'd, in that it may in &s;ome Mea&s;ure pro|ceed from a political Rea&s;on of State; eve|ry Potentate concern'd being de&s;irous, nay, deeming it of ab&s;olute Nece&s;&s;ity, to keep up the almost dejected Hearts of their di&s;pirited Va&s;&s;als, and to in&s;pire them with fre&s;h Cou|rage, by giving them every Year repeated Hopes of a &s;peedy End of this bloody, expen|&s;ive, and con&s;equently de&s;tructive War. This, perhaps, may have been the chief Rea&s;on, for I can di&s;cover no other, that may have induc'd &s;ome of the Princes, who are now engag'd in Arms, to connive at the great number of &s;currilous lying Pamphlets, as well News-Papers as others, and to permit them to be publi&s;h'd and &s;pread abroad through|out all their Dominions, impunibly and with|out the lea&s;t Controul. I have ob&s;erv'd, and any one who has read the Relations they have given us, with the least, that is, with more Attention than they de&s;erve, may have done &s;o too, that all the Actions, which, du|ring
<PB REF="8">
the whole Cour&s;e of this War, have hap|pen'd between the Armies abroad, have been related in the &s;ame manner, nay, almo&s;t in the &s;ame Words. So mi&s;erably are the&s;e pi|tiful. Scriblers put to their &s;hifts for new Words, and a fre&s;h manner of Lying, to fill up the length of their Papers. With them, the beaten Party is very mode&s;t if he lay not Claim to the Victory, or at least to a drawn Battel; for, excepting in the Battels of <HI>Landen</HI> and <HI>Turin</HI>, where, the Advantages were &s;o great as to &s;trike the Eyes of the mo&s;t Incredulous, and to leave &s;carce any Room for Di&s;gui&s;e, he has always kill'd as many of the Enemies, as he lo&s;t of his own Troops; or el&s;e he came off with little Lo&s;s, and made his Retreat in good Order: Be|&s;ides, were his Lo&s;s ever &s;o great, he has daily found it to be le&s;s than it was at first reported, by rea&s;on of the great Number of Soldiers that had been given over for kill'd or taken, but were continually coming back to the Camp. On the other Hand, he, who got the better of the Day, has never failed to magnify his Advantages proportionably: He has routed his Enemies to that Degree, that, as we were told, we had rea&s;on to believe, they would never be able to recruit their Armies, nor ever more &s;hew their Fa|ces in a Camp. To this wretched Plight have our Enemies been reduc'd at the end of
<PB REF="9">
&s;everal Campaigns; and yet the &s;ucceeding Spring has beheld this <HI>Hydra</HI>, with two Heads &s;prouted out in the room of one that was cut off; and we have met in the Field a more terrible Mon&s;ter to encounter. Their Narratives of other Matters of Fact are of the like Stamp, and I appeal to any impar|tial Per&s;on what Credit is to be given to them. The Governments them&s;elves have, no doubt, had more authentick Advices; tho', as I hinted before, they have, for certain Rea|&s;ons of State, &s;uffer'd the&s;e Impo&s;itions to be <HI>Po&s;t-Man'd</HI> and <HI>Po&s;t-Boy'd</HI> upon the Pub|lick. And with this Encouragement the&s;e im|perfect and lying Relations are bungled and patch'd up together, and pa&s;s currently with &s;ome, for what they fal&s;ely and &s;candalou&s;ly call them&s;elves, <HI>The Annals of the Reigns of our Sovereigns</HI>. But the&s;e impudent News-Writers &s;top not here, for they pre&s;ume to intrude into the Councils and Cabinets of Princes, and give the World an Account of what pa&s;&s;es, and is re&s;olv'd on there, as well in regard to our own Affairs as tho&s;e of Fo|reign States. An In&s;olence without Exam|ple, 'till of late Days.</P>
<P>Now, that the following Letters may not be thought to de&s;erve as little Credit as the Relations of which I have been &s;peaking; and that too the rather, becau&s;e they treat of Affairs of the &s;ame Nature; it will be
<PB REF="10">
nece&s;&s;ary to premi&s;e, in a few Words, what they contain, and by whom, as well as to whom they were written.</P>
<P>First then, They were written in the Year <HI>1674</HI>, all of them, except two to Sir <HI>Robert Southwell</HI>, to the Earl of <HI>Arlington</HI>, then Secretary of State, by Sir <HI>Richard Bul&s;trode</HI>, who then re&s;ided at the Court of <HI>Bruxelles</HI>, as Agent for King <HI>Charles</HI> the Second, and they contain the Hi&s;tory of all the remarkable Tran&s;actions in the Low Countries, in <HI>Al|&s;atia</HI> and <HI>Burgundy</HI>, during the Campaign of that Year, when the <HI>Imperiali&s;ts, Spaniards</HI>, and <HI>Dutch</HI> were engag'd in War against the <HI>French</HI>. This was that Campaign in which was fought the memorable Battel of <HI>Seneff</HI>, between the Confederates under the Command of the Prince of <HI>Orange</HI>, and the Army of <HI>France</HI> commanded by the Prince of <HI>Conde;</HI> which I chu&s;e particularly to mention, that the Reader may take notice, that it is no new Cu&s;tom for both Sides to a&s;cribe to them&s;elves the Honour of the Victory; for they did &s;o even then, and made Rejoicings too every where for it. The&s;e Letters evidently &s;hew to which &s;ide it inclin'd, and whoever reads them will, I believe, be of Opinion, that this Relation of that Battel is the only impartial and true Account of it, that is yet any where extant. We may affirm the &s;ame too of the other Oc|currences that are here related; as of the
<PB REF="11">
Account of the Battel that happen'd the &s;ame Year on the Banks of the <HI>Neckar</HI>, between the <HI>Imperiali&s;ts</HI> and the <HI>French;</HI> the first of them commanded by the Duke of <HI>Lorrain</HI>, the last by Mar&s;hal <HI>Turenne;</HI> and al&s;o of the &s;everal Sieges, and other military Exploits of that Campaign; together, with all the &s;ecret Cabals and Intrigues of the then Court of <HI>Bru&s;&s;els;</HI> all which is the Subject of the&s;e Letters, which are written with &s;uch an Air of Candour, Integrity, and Impartiality, as plainly evinces them to be authentick, and would in a manner command our Belief, e|ven tho' we were ignorant of the Author.</P>
<P>As for the Style in which they are written, it is purely Epi&s;tolatory, &s;uch as one Gentleman writes off-hand to another, and &s;uch as best becomes Compo&s;ures of this Nature, when they are written as they ought to be: For they require not elaborate Elegancies, but &s;hould have only a native Clearne&s;s and Bre|vity; they &s;hould not con&s;i&s;t of ful&s;ome Com|pliments, but &s;hould have a re&s;pectful kind of Plainne&s;s and Familiarity, to affect only the Humour of tho&s;e to whom they are inten|ded. In Letters like the&s;e, the Souls of Men &s;hould appear undre&s;s'd, and in a negli|gent Habit, not trick'd up with artful Gaw|deries, or the &s;tudy'd Ornaments of Rheto|rick; and &s;uch I dare affirm the following Letters to be.</P>
<P><PB REF="12">As for the &s;ubmi&s;&s;ive Expre&s;&s;ions the Au|thor u&s;es in the Conclu&s;ion of his Letters, as that of <HI>Laying my &s;elf low at your Lord|&s;hip's Feet with all Zeal and Humility</HI>, it was a Compliment us'd by Gentlemen of the best Quality, one towards another in tho&s;e Times, tho' now laid a&s;ide; nay, I cou'd give In&s;tances of Sub&s;criptions more humble and abject in the Letters of &s;everal Envoys, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> &s;ome of whom are now living, than are to be found any where in our Author.</P>
<P>It will be nece&s;&s;ary, in the next Place, to give &s;ome Account of our Author, that may &s;erve rather for the Information of his Rea|ders, than for the Increa&s;e of his Fame, which &s;tands not in need of any &s;uch Helps to e&s;tabli&s;h it.</P>
<P>He was de&s;cended of the ancient Family of <HI>Bul&s;trode</HI>, in the County of <HI>Bucks</HI>. Their first Name was <HI>Shobbington</HI>, and came to be chang'd into that of <HI>Bul&s;trode</HI> by this re|markable Adventure, which I have learn'd from &s;ome of the Family them&s;elves. The Story, as they report it, runs thus. When <HI>William</HI> the Conqueror had &s;ubdu'd this Kingdom to his Obedience, he granted the E|&s;tate of the <HI>Shobbington</HI>'s, who&s;e capital Seat, now likewi&s;e call'd <HI>Bul&s;trode</HI>'s, was &s;itua|ted in the middle of a fine Park, by <HI>Gerard</HI>'s Cro&s;s near <HI>Beaconsfield</HI>, and had been in their Family for &s;everal Ages before, to a certain
<PB REF="13">
<HI>Norman</HI> Lord who came over with him: of which the <HI>Shobbington</HI>, who then enjoy'd it, having notice, he re&s;olv'd rather to die upon the Spot, than tamely to &s;uffer him&s;elf to be turn'd out of Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of that Inheritance, which had de&s;cended to him from his Ance|&s;tors. In this Re&s;olution he arm'd his Ser|vants and his Tenants, who&s;e Number was very con&s;iderable. Upon which the <HI>Norman</HI> Lord, who had Advice of it, obtain'd of the King a thou&s;and of his Regular Troops, to help him to take Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the E&s;tate by Force: whereupon <HI>Shobbington</HI> apply'd him|&s;elf to his Relations and Neighbours to a&s;&s;ist him; and the two ancient Families of the <HI>Hambden</HI>'s and <HI>Penn</HI>'s took Arms, together with their Servants and Tenants, and came to his Relief. When they were all joyn'd, they ca&s;t up Works, who&s;e Remains appear to this Day, in the Place where the Park now is; and the <HI>Norman</HI> Lord, with his Forces, came and encamp'd before their Intrench|ments. Now whether it were that they wanted Hor&s;es, or not, is uncertain; but the Story goes, That having manag'd a par|cel of Bulls, they mounted them, and &s;ally|ing out of their Intrenchments in the Night, &s;urpriz'd the <HI>Normans</HI> in their Camp, kill'd many of them, and put the rest to Flight. The King having Intelligence of it, and not thinking it &s;afe for him, while his
<PB REF="14">
Power was yet new and un&s;ettled, to drive a daring and ob&s;tinate People to De&s;pair, &s;ent a Herald to them, to know what they would have, and promis'd <HI>Shobbington</HI> a Safe Con|duct, if he would come to Court; which <HI>Shobbington</HI> accordingly did, riding thither upon a Bull. Being introduc'd into the Royal Pre&s;ence, the King a&s;k'd him his Demands, and why he alone dar'd to re&s;ist, when the rest of the Kingdom had &s;ubmitted to his Go|vernment, and own'd him for their Sove|reign? <HI>Shobbington</HI> an&s;wer'd, That he and his Ance&s;tors had long been Inhabitants of this I&s;land, and had enjoy'd that E&s;tate for many Years; that if the King would permit him to keep it, he would become his Subject, and be faithful to him, as he had been to his Predece&s;&s;ors. The King gave him his Royal Word, that he would, and immediately grant|ed him the free Enjoyment of his E&s;tate: Upon which the Family was from thence call'd <HI>Shobbington, ali&agrave;s Bul&s;trode;</HI> but in Proce&s;s of Time the fir&s;t Name was di&s;con|tinued, and that of <HI>Bul&s;trode</HI> only has re|main'd to them. The Truth of this Story is not only confirm'd by long Tradition in the Family, but by &s;everal Memoirs which they have &s;till remaining, and by the Ruins of the Works, that are to this Day &s;een in the Park of <HI>Bul&s;trodes</HI>, as well as by the Crest of their Arms, which is, <HI>a Bull's Head cabo&s;s'd
<PB REF="15">
Gules, attir'd Or, between two Wings Sa|ble</HI>. The E&s;tate of <HI>Bul&s;trodes</HI> remain'd in, and continu'd to be, the Seat of the Family, till about forty Years ago, when it was first &s;old, and has &s;ince pa&s;s'd through &s;everal Hands. The Earl of <HI>Portland</HI> now enjoys it by Inheritance from his Father, who was the last that purchas'd it. But to return to our Author.</P>
<P>Sir <HI>Richard Bul&s;trode</HI> was born in the Year of our Lord <HI>1610</HI>. He was the el|dest Son of <HI>Edward Bul&s;trode</HI> of the <HI>Inner-Temple</HI>, <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR> a very learned Lawyer, as ap|pears by his Book <HI>of Reports</HI>, a Work in great E&s;teem to this Day. The first Years of his Youth were, as u&s;ual, &s;pent at School; whence he was remov'd to <HI>Pembroke</HI> Hall in <HI>Cambridge</HI>, where he continu'd his Stu|dies for &s;everal Years. In <HI>1633</HI>, being then about twenty three Years of Age, he writ a Poem on the Birth of the Duke of <HI>York</HI>, which is &s;till extant in the Collections of the Poems of that Univer&s;ity. From <HI>Cambridge</HI> he went to the Inns of Court, and was en|ter'd in the &s;ame Hou&s;e with his Father. He became a Barri&s;ter at Law, and pra|ctis'd as &s;uch till the breaking out of the Civil Wars, when his Affection to the King's Cau&s;e made him quit the Gown, and drew him to the Army; where he behav'd him&s;elf with &s;o much Prudence, Bravery, and Con|duct,
<PB REF="16">
that King <HI>Charles</HI> the <HI>1^&s;^t</HI> &s;oon made him Adjutant General of his Army, and af|terwards Quarter-Ma&s;ter General; in which Post he continued to &s;erve till the di&s;banding of the King's Forces at <HI>Truro</HI>.</P>
<P>When that unnatural Rebellion was ended, and King <HI>Charles</HI> the <HI>2^d</HI> happily re&s;tor'd, our Author after &s;ome Years Atten|dance on the Court, and being now above &s;ixty years of Age, was at length, in Reward of his long and faithful Services to the Crown, &s;ent to re&s;ide at <HI>Bru&s;&s;els</HI> in Quality of Agent for that Prince; and from thence he writ the&s;e Letters, with which we here pre&s;ent the Publick.</P>
<P>In the Year <HI>1675.</HI> he return'd to <HI>England</HI> to give the King an Account of his Negotia|tions, with which his Maje&s;ty was &s;o well &s;a|tisfy'd, that he conferr'd on him the Honour of Knighthood, and in a few Months &s;ent him back again to that Court with the Cha|racter of his Re&s;ident there. This is confirm'd by the Credential Letters, which the King writ in his behalf to the Duke <HI>de Villa Her|mo&s;a</HI>, then Governour General of the <HI>Spani&s;h Netherlands</HI>, and which are as follows.</P>
