<HEAD>To the mo&s;t Illu&s;trious and mo&s;t Excellent Lord, <HI>Charles de Arogana</HI>, Duke <HI>de Villa Hermo&s;a</HI>, Count <HI>de Luna</HI>, Go|vernour General, for the mo&s;t Serene King of <HI>Spain</HI>, in the Provinces of the <HI>Netherlands</HI> and <HI>Burgundy</HI>, Our mo&s;t Dear Friend.</HEAD>
<P><HI>CHarles</HI> the Se|cond, by the Grace of God King of <HI>Great Britain, France</HI> and <HI>Ireland</HI>, Defen|der of the Faith, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> To the mo&s;t Illu&s;tri|ous and mo&s;t Excel|lent Lord, <HI>Charles de Arogana</HI>, Duke <HI>de Vil|la Hermo&s;a</HI>, Count <HI>de Luna</HI>, Governour General, from the Part of the mo&s;t Se|rene King of <HI>Spain</HI>,
<PB REF="18">
of the Provinces of the <HI>Netherlands</HI> and of <HI>Burgundy</HI>, Our mo&s;t Dear Friend, Greeting. Mo&s;t Illu|&s;trious and mo&s;t Ex|cellent Lord, mo&s;t Dear Friend; Our Beloved and Faithful Subject <HI>Richard Bul|&s;trode</HI>, whom We &s;ent formerly to re&s;ide at <HI>Bru&s;&s;els</HI> with the Cha|racter of Our Agent, return'd lately to Us: Among other Things of which he has in|form'd Us, he has &s;poken at large of your Excellency's Af|fection towards Us, and of your good Will to our Subjects. We now &s;end back the &s;ame <HI>Richard Bul|&s;trode</HI> to <HI>Bru&s;&s;els</HI> in Quality of Our Re&s;i|dent, having like|wi&s;e conferr'd on him the Honour of Knighthood, that
<PB REF="19">
your Excellency may know, that We are well &s;atisfy'd with him, in the Di&s;charge of his former Mini|&s;try: Nor do We be|lieve that he has been di&s;plea&s;ing to your Excellency, by the Letters you writ to Us, of the 12^t^h of <HI>December</HI> la&s;t pa&s;t, which We receiv'd by his Hands. He has In&s;tructions from Us to pay all due Re|&s;pect to your Excel|lency, and as long as he continues in tho&s;e Provinces, to be no le&s;s diligent in cul|tivating the Friend|&s;hip there is between Us and the mo&s;t Se|rene Catholick King, than in taking Care of Our and Our Subjects Affairs. Wherefore We doubt not but your Excellency will kindly receive Our
<PB REF="20">
&s;aid Re&s;ident, and give Credit to him in all Things he &s;hall make known to you in Our Name. And &s;o We heartily com|mend your Excellen|cy to the Protection of the Almighty. Gi|ven at our Court at <HI>Whitehall</HI> the 28^t^h day of <HI>January</HI>, 1675/6.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Your Excellency's Good Friend, CHARLES R.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</LETTER>
<P>Sir <HI>Richard Bul&s;trode</HI> continu'd Re&s;ident at <HI>Bru&s;&s;els</HI> till the Death of King <HI>Charles</HI> the <HI>2^d</HI>, when his Succe&s;&s;or King <HI>James</HI> the <HI>2^d</HI> conferr'd on him a yet higher Honour, and made him his Envoy at the &s;ame Court, where he &s;erv'd the Crown in that Mini&s;try, till his unfortunate Ma&s;ter was forc'd to retire into <HI>France:</HI> whither his faithful Envoy &s;oon follow'd him, and ended his Days at the Court of St. <HI>Germans, Octob. 3.</HI> N. S.
<PB REF="21">
being a hundred and one Years old and two Months.</P>
<P>He was twice marry'd: His first Wife was Daughter of <HI>Edward Dineley</HI> of <HI>Charl|ton</HI>, near <HI>Eve&s;ham</HI>, in the County of <HI>Worce|&s;ter</HI>, <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR>, and Sister to Sir <HI>Edward Dineley</HI> lately deceas'd: By her he had two Sons, who are both living. <HI>Whitlock Bul&s;trode</HI>, <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR> the youngest of them, a Barri&s;ter at Law, is now one of the Commi&s;&s;ioners of Exci&s;e. And this honourable Gentleman gives me leave to a&s;&s;ure the Publick, that he has &s;een the Ori|ginals of the&s;e Letters, and knows them to be his Father Sir <HI>Richard Bul&s;trode</HI>'s own Hand-writing: which ought to be Satisfa|ction enough to the World that they are genu|ine, and render it needle&s;s to give any Ac|count how we came by them.</P>
<P>His &s;econd Wife was Daughter of M. <HI>Stam|ford</HI>, who was Envoy to the Court of <HI>Eng|land</HI> from the Duke of <HI>Newbourg</HI>, now Ele|ctor <HI>Palatine</HI> of the <HI>Rhine</HI>. By her he has left behind him three Sons and four Daugh|ters, &s;everal of whom are under twenty years of Age; but his elde&s;t Son now living, whom he had by his former Wife, is Sixty one and upwards.</P>
<P>He enjoy'd a wonderful Firmne&s;s of Mind and Strength of Body to the very last. After he was four&s;core Years old and more, he would often walk twelve Miles in a Morning,
<PB REF="22">
and &s;tudy as many Hours in a Day. And tho' it may &s;eem a Paradox, old tho' he was, it cannot &s;trictly be &s;aid, that he dy'd of old Age: The Di&s;ea&s;e that carry'd him off, was a Stoppage at his Stomach, caus'd by an In|dige&s;tion: Neverthele&s;s had proper Remedies been apply'd, he might, in all probability, have worn out &s;everal Years longer: But his Phy&s;ician, who under&s;tood his Con&s;titution, being out of the way, tho&s;e that were &s;ent for to his Relief, durst not, by rea&s;on of his Age, give him a Vomit; the want of which, 'tis thought, ha&s;ten'd his End.</P>
<P>He was accompl&s;h'd with all manner of Abilities for the greate&s;t Bu&s;ine&s;s: He per|fectly under&s;tood the Interests of Princes, and the Arts and Intriegues of Courts, and often tran&s;acted Affairs of the utmo&s;t Importance: In all which he ever behav'd him&s;elf with in|defatigable Integrity, and un&s;u&s;pected Secrecy. And certainly his Conduct mu&s;t have been ve|ry unblameable, which had been try'd in Bu|&s;ine&s;s of the highe&s;t Con&s;equence, and pra|ctis'd in the hazardous Secrets of Courts and Cabinets, and yet nothing di&s;graceful was ever alledg'd against it.</P>
<P>He was throughly acquainted with the an|cient and the modern Languages, and had been very conver&s;ant in the Lecture of the best Authors; which he not only retain'd in
<PB REF="23">
his Memory, but had dige&s;ted likewi&s;e in his Judgment. With the&s;e Advantages he left behind him &s;everal Treati&s;es of his own com|po&s;ing; as the Lives of his three Ma&s;ters, King <HI>Charles</HI> the <HI>1^&s;^t</HI>, King <HI>Charles</HI> the <HI>2^d</HI>, and King <HI>James</HI> the <HI>2^d</HI>, and E&s;&s;ays on &s;eve|ral Subjects; with all which we hope to oblige the Publick in a &s;hort time; none of them having yet &s;een the Light, except the Life of King <HI>James</HI> the <HI>2^d</HI>, which has been lately printed at <HI>Rome</HI>. His E&s;&s;ays are ve|ry much commended by judicious Per&s;ons to whom he had &s;hewn them in his Life-time: He de&s;ign'd them for the Pre&s;s, and we ex|pect that they will e'er long be tran&s;mitted hither for that purpo&s;e.</P>
<P>When he was above eighty Years of Age he compos'd in Latin Ver&s;e <HI>185</HI>, as well Ele|gies as Epigrams, all of them on divine Sub|jects. Tho&s;e likewi&s;e he intended to be prin|ted, and &s;ome time before his Death, &s;ent them over to his Son, <HI>Whitlock Bul&s;trode</HI>, <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR> for that purpo&s;e: But this worthy Gentleman, reflecting with good Rea&s;on, that a Book of Divine Poems would perhaps agree but ill with the Temper of the pre&s;ent Age, which &s;eems to delight more in War, than in Piety, has hitherto kept them to him&s;elf, and re&s;erves them for a more favourable Opportu|nity. However to give the World a Ta&s;te of
<PB REF="24">
them, as well as of his E&s;&s;ays, we have here, till they are publi&s;h'd together in one Volume, &s;ubjoin'd &s;ome of tho&s;e Poems, together with a Letter, which, a few Years ago, he writ to his above-mention'd Son, on the Subject of Retirement: And thus we conclude this &s;hort Account of our Author.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1>
<HEAD>Florilegium Metricum, &s;ive Poemata Sacra. A D Candidum Lectorem.</HEAD>
<L>CArmina quiquondam &s;crip&s;i florentibus annis</L>
<L>Mollia, nunc moe&s;tis carmina &s;cribo modis;</L>
<L>Qui mihi Sacratae dictant &s;cribenda Camoenae</L>
<L>Dum veris Elegi fletibus ora rigant.</L>
<L>Sed re&s;onante tub&acirc; quid inepte carmina &s;cribo?</L>
<L>Non quadrant Mu&s;is tempora no&s;tra piis.</L>
<L>Tempora plena malis, &amp; quae pejora timemus,</L>
<L>Tempora fortunis invidio&s;a meis.</L>
<L>Scrip&s;imus i&s;ta tamen quamvis mihin nulla voluptas</L>
<L>Scribendi tri&s;ti carmina duct a manu.</L>
<L>Nec laeto po&s;&s;um ver&s;us componere vultu,</L>
<L>Non nobis mi&s;eris convenit ille lepos.</L>
<L>Induo lugubres vultus, &amp; &s;ic color ater</L>
<L>Carminibus melius convenit i&s;te meis.</L>
<L>Grande opus aggredior, Lector &s;tudio&s;e, labori</L>
<L>Annue, dum parvo carmine magna l$quor.</L>
<L><PB REF="25">Exue crudeles animos pauli&s;per amicos</L>
<L>Indue, cen&s;orem te decet e&s;&s;e meum.</L>
<L>Nec dedigneris &s;teriles de me&s;&s;e maniplos,</L>
<L>Quos dat non fallax, &s;ed male cultus ager.</L>
<L>Parva licet mea dona, hilari tamen accipe vultu</L>
<L>Haec &s;acros Vates gloria &s;ola decet.</L>
<L>Di&s;pliceat frons atra licet &s;um foetus Olympo,</L>
<L>Foetaque &s;unt &s;ummo carmina no&s;tra Deo.</L>
<L>Nomine tuta &s;uo &s;e o&s;tendunt, &amp; &s;ua facta</L>
<L>Me licet immerito vate canente canunt.</L>
<L>Nil agitant mortale, Deus, Deus ip&s;e canentis</L>
<L>A&s;pirat caeptis illius igne calent.</L>
<L>Illius urgentur &s;timulis, illoque premente</L>
<L>Numine, non hominem carmina no&s;tra &s;onant.</L>
<L>Vertice ab aethereo Chri&s;tum decanto migrantem,</L>
<L>Qualiter intact&acirc; Virgine factus homo.</L>
<L>Si quos protulerim non dignos vivere ver&s;us,</L>
<L>Et qui debuerant nocte &s;ilente premi,</L>
<L>Torpuit ingenium no&s;trum torpente &s;enecta</L>
<L>Dedidicit numeris currere Mu&s;a &s;uis.</L>
<L>Nam &s;ubeunt anni fragiles &amp; inertior aetas</L>
<L>Imminet &amp; vitae frigida bruma meae,</L>
<L>Nunc mihi Bul&s;trode mea $ecta labantia nutant.</L>
<L>Nec vigor e&s;t animi, &s;erpit in o&s;&s;a gelu.</L>
<L>Tempore mutato mores mutantur &amp; ip&s;i.</L>
